&ldquo;It&rsquo;s good to learn from your mistakes. It&rsquo;s better to learn from other people&rsquo;s mistakes.&quot;
 -Warren Buffett
This one’s always been a bee in my bonnet. It inspired a rather neurotic energy and sense of behind-ness. So many biographies to read, so many interviews to listen to. But having given myself chances to make my own mistakes in recent years, I’ve come to the conclusion: you can’t learn from others mistakes until you’ve first begun to learn from your own.

Gleb Posobin &ldquo;Your own ideas mostly seem trivial to you because you have the right concept structures in place to support them. You wouldn&rsquo;t come up with these ideas otherwise. So it&rsquo;s easier to notice your own ideas in a dialogue: your friend has different concept structures and notices them.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Corollary: don&rsquo;t be afraid to say obvious things.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Corollary 2: it is ok if it seems to you that you do not have nontrivial ideas of your own.
